  What's still wrong, prioritized

  The residual false positives are all variants of the same problem: first-shell-isomorphic but topologically distinct compounds. Concrete examples:

  - Spinel vs sphalerite-derived (both have cation CN=4 + cation CN=6 + anion CN=4)
  - Phenakite/willemite vs sphalerite (both all-CN=4)
  - Layered ABX₂ vs CaFe₂O₄-type (different sharing modes but similar bond multiplicity)
  - Borates vs sulfide chains (when the bond histograms accidentally match)

  TopologyCost can't catch these — by construction. They genuinely have the same first-shell bond-element histogram. The structural difference lives in:
  1. Polyhedral connectivity (corner vs edge vs face sharing) → captured by PolyhedralCost
  2. Bond-angle distributions → captured by BondAngleCost
  3. Bond-length distributions → captured by BondLengthCost

  We measured earlier that on Mg₂SiO₄ ↔ MgAl₂O₄ specifically:
  - Topology = 0
  - BondLength = 1.63
  - BondAngle = 0.48
  - Polyhedral = 1.27

  The clustering is currently using TopologyCost only. Switching to a WeightedSum([1.0 × Topology, 0.5 × Polyhedral, 0.3 × BondLength]) would shrink Families 1, 2, 7, 23, 31, 42, 44, 55 — at threshold 0.1 most of these would split
  into chemistry-correct sub-families.

